{{italic title}} {{Unreferenced stub|auto=yes|date=December 2009}} '''''Ex Parte Bowman''''' 61 [[U.S.P.Q.2d]] 1669 (Bd. Pat. App. & Int. 2001) was a decision by the U.S. [[Board of Patent Appeals and Interferences]] which asserted that in order to be [[patent-eligible]], a process had to involve or promote the technological arts. This decision was overruled by the Board's subsequent ''[[Ex Parte Lundgren]]'' decision, but the Board's and then the Federal Circuit's [[In re Bilski]] opinion then superseded ''Lundgren''. ''In re Bilski'', however, rejects use of "not in the technological arts" as a basis for a rejection, although it seems to accept the concept when differently named. ''Bilski'' is now pending on writ of [[certiorari]].
