{{Language-stub}}

{{Hungarian language}} There are numerous [[regular sound correspondence]]s between [[Hungarian language|Hungarian]] and the other [[Uralic languages]]. For example, Hungarian ''á'' corresponds to [[Khanty language|Khanty]] ''o'' in certain positions, and Hungarian ''h'' corresponds to Khanty ''x'', while Hungarian final ''z'' corresponds to Khanty final ''t''. These can be seen in Hungarian ''ház'' ("house") and Khanty ''xot'' ("house"), or Hungarian ''száz'' ("hundred") and Khanty ''sot'' ("hundred").
Hungarian and [[Khanty language|Khanty]] are closely connected, either genealogically or as part of a [[sprachbund|language area]]. The distance between Hungarian and the Finnic languages is greater, but the correspondences are also regular. The relationship is most obvious when comparing all Uralic languages together, for then individual [[idiosyncrasy|idiosyncrasies]] are averaged out, but here we will just compare Hungarian with [[Finnish language|Finnish]] and [[Estonian language|Estonian]] (two Finnic languages).
==Stop consonants==
===Word-initially=== One important innovation of Hungarian is the [[lenition]] of the [[stop consonant]]s *p *k in initial position.
*Hungarian {{IPA|/f/}} corresponds to Finnish and Estonian {{IPA|/p/}} (compare English ''fish'' to Italian ''pesce''):
{| class="wikitable" |- !Proto-Uralic !Hungarian !Finnish !Estonian !meaning |- |''*puxe'' |''fa'' |''puu'' |''puu'' |tree |- |''*pala'' |''falat'' |''pala'' |''pala'' |bit, bite |- |''*pele-'' |''fél'' |''pelätä'' |''pelgama'' |to fear |- |''*pesä'' |''fészek'' |''pesä'' |''pesa'' |nest |- |''*pilwe'' |''felhő'' |''pilvi'' |''pilv'' |cloud |- |''*puna-'' |''fon'' |''punoa'' |''punuma'' |to plait |- |''*päŋe'' |''fő'' |''pää'' |''peä'' |head |}
*Before front vowels (''e é i í y ä ö ő ü ű''), Hungarian {{IPA|/k/}} corresponds to Finnish and Estonian {{IPA|/k/}}:
{| class="wikitable" |- !Proto-Uralic !Hungarian !Finnish !Estonian !meaning |- |''*küńele'' |''könny'' |''kyynel'' |''küünistama'' |tear |- |''*käte'' |''kéz'' |''käsi'' |''käsi'' |hand, arm |- |''*kiwe'' |''kő'' |''kivi'' |''kivi'' |stone |}
*Before back vowels (''a á o ó u ú''), Hungarian {{IPA|/h/}} corresponds to Finnish and Estonian {{IPA|/k/}} (as English {{IPA|/h/}} in ''hound'' corresponds to Latin {{IPA|/k/}} in ''canis'')
{| class="wikitable" |- !Proto-Uralic !Hungarian !Finnish !Estonian !meaning |- |''*kala'' |''hal'' |''kala'' |''kala'' |fish |- |''*kota'' |''ház'' |''kota'' |''koda'' |house (Hung.), hut (Finn. and Est.) |- |''*kuńśe'' |''húgy'' |''kusi'' |''kusi'' |urine |}
The third stop inherited from [[Proto-Uralic]], *t, did not undergo such a change. *Hungarian initial {{IPA|/t/}} corresponds to Finnish and Estonian {{IPA|/t/}}:
{| class="wikitable" |- !Proto-Uralic !Hungarian !Finnish !Estonian !meaning |- |''*tälwä'' |''tél'' |''talvi'' |''talv'' |winter |- |''*tumte-'' |''tud'' |''tuntea'' |''tundma'' |to know |- |''*towke'' |''tavasz'' |''touko'' | |spring |}
===Word-medially===
In the middle of words (note that due to the loss of the word final vocals in the Old Hungarian period these are now at the end of the words), Hungarian has also lenited original stops, but in a different fashion.
* Hungarian {{IPA|/p k/}} correspond to Finnish and Estonian geminate stops {{IPA|/pp kk/}}: {| class="wikitable" |- !Proto-Uralic !Hungarian !Finnish !Estonian !meaning |- |''*ëppe'' |''após'' |''appi'' | |father-in-law |- |''*säppä'' |''epe'' |''sappi'' |''sapp'' |gall |- |''*lappɜ'' |''lapos'' |''lappea'' |''lapp'' |flat |- |''*lükkä-'' |''lök'' |''lykätä'' : ''lykkää-'' |''lükkama'' |to push |}
* Hungarian {{IPA|/t/}} corresponds to the Finnish and Estonian two-stop cluster {{IPA|/tk/}}: {| class="wikitable" |- !Proto-Uralic !Hungarian !Finnish !Estonian !meaning |- |''*kütke-.'' |''köt'' |''kytkeä'' |''kütke'' |to bind, to join (Estonian: "halter", a derivative) |- |''*'' |''tat'' (dialectal) | |''tõtkes'' |[[tench]] |} (No examples where a word with original *tt would have survived in both Hungarian and Finnic are known, but cases testifying for the development of *tt to /tt/ in Finnic and /t/ in Hungarian can be set up with the help of the other Uralic languages.)
* Hungarian {{IPA|/d/}} corresponds to Finnish and Estonian {{IPA|/nt/}} (which may alternate with {{IPA|/nn/}}): {| class="wikitable" |- !Proto-Uralic !Hungarian !Finnish !Estonian !meaning |- |''*ëmta-'' |''ad'' |''antaa'' |''andma'' |to give |- |''*jänte'' | ''ideg'' | ''jänne'' : ''jäntee-'' | | nerve (Hung.; a derivative), string, sinew (Fi.) |- |''*omte'' |''odú'' |''ontelo'' |''õõnes'' | hollow |- |''*tumte-'' |''tud'' |''tuntea'' |''tundma'' |to know |- |}
(Again, with the help of the other Uralic languages, the analogous developments *mp *ŋk → Hungarian /b g/, Finnic /mp ŋk/ could be supported.)
* Hungarian {{IPA|/v/}} corresponds to Finnish and Estonian {{IPA|/p/}}: {| class="wikitable" |- !Proto-Uralic !Hungarian !Finnish !Estonian !meaning |- |''*kepä'' |''kevés'' |''kepeä'' |''kebja'' |few (Hung.), light (Finnic) |- |''*čupa'' |''sovány'' |''hupe-ne-'' |''huba'' |thin (Hung.) |}
* Hungarian {{IPA|/z/}} corresponds to Finnish and Estonian {{IPA|/t/}} (which can alternate with {{IPA|/d/}} or zero, and becomes {{IPA|/s/}} before {{IPA|/i/}}):
{| class="wikitable" |- !Proto-Uralic !Hungarian !Finnish !Estonian !meaning |- |''*kota'' |''ház'' |''kota'' |''koda'' |house (Hung.), hut (Finnic) |- |''*käte'' |''kéz'' |''käsi'' : ''käden'' : ''käte-'' |''käsi'' : ''käe'' : ''käte-'' |hand, arm |- |''*pata'' |''fazék'' |''pata'' |''pada'' |pot |- |''*mete'' |''méz'' |''mesi'' : ''meden'' : ''mete-'' |''mesi'': ''mee'' : ''mete-'' |honey |}
* Hungarian zero, here always preceding a long vowel, corresponds to Finnish and Estonian {{IPA|/k/}} by itself (which may alternate with zero or /h/) and as the first member of a consonant cluster: {| class="wikitable" |- !Proto-Uralic !Hungarian !Finnish !Estonian !meaning |- |''*ikene'' |''íny'' |''ien'' : ''ikene-'' |''ige'' |palate (Hung. & Es.), gums (Fi.) |- |''*joke'' |''jó'' |''joki'' |''jõgi'' |river (only in placenames in Hung.) |- |''*mëksa'' |''máj'' |''maksa'' |''maks'' |liver |- |''*näke-'' |''néz'' |''nähdä'' : ''näke-'' |''nägema'' |to see |- |''*sükśe'' |''ősz'' |''syksy'' |''sügis'' |autumn |}
==Sibilant consonants== Two different regular correspondences can be found in Hungarian for Finnish and Estonian {{IPA|/s/}}. The first is Hungarian {{IPA|/s/}}:
{| class="wikitable" |- !Proto-Uralic !Hungarian !Finnish !Estonian !meaning |- |''*śata'' |''száz'' |''sata'' |''sata'' |hundred |- |''*śüδäme'' |''szív'' |''sydän'' |''süda'' |heart |- |''*śilmä'' |''szem'' |''silmä'' |''silm'' |eye |- |''*śuwe'' |''száj'' |''suu'' |''suu'' |mouth |- |''*pesä'' |''fészek'' |''pesä'' |''pesa'' |nest |}
The second is Hungarian zero:
{| class="wikitable" |- !Proto-Uralic !Hungarian !Finnish !Estonian !meaning |- |''*sewe-'' |''eszik'' : ''ev-'' |''syödä'' |''sööma'' |to eat |- |''*säppä'' |''epe'' |''sappi'' |''sapp'' |gall |- |''*sëne'' |''ín'' |''suoni'' |''soon'' |sinew, (Finnic also) vein |- |''*süle'' |''öl'' |''syli'' |''süli'' |bosom |}
These two correspondences represent two different original consonants. {{IPA|/s/}} : {{IPA|/s/}} is reconstructed as originating in Proto-Uralic *ś, while ∅ : {{IPA|/s/}} is reconstructed as Proto-Uralic *s. Both correspondences can be seen simultaneously in the word for "autumn" (see above under *-k-), from Proto-Uralic *sükśi.
==Sonorant consonants== * Hungarian liquid consonants {{IPA|/l r/}} correspond to Finnish and Estonian {{IPA|/l r/}}: {| class="wikitable" |- !Proto-Uralic !Hungarian !Finnish !Estonian !meaning |- |''*ora'' |''ár'' |''ora'' |''ora'' |awl (Hung., Es.), thorn (Fi.) |- |''*alla'' |''alatt'' |''alla'' |''all'' |under |- |''*elä-'' |''él'' |''elää'' |''elama'' |to live |- |''*kala-'' |''hal'' |''kuolla'' |''koolema'' |to die |- |''*läme'' |''lé'' : ''lev-'' |''liemi'' |''leem'' |liquid (Hung.), broth (Finnic) |- |''*ńale-'' |''nyal'' |''nuolla'' |''noolima'' |to lick |- |''*ńële'' |''nyíl'' |''nuoli'' |''nool'' |arrow |- |''*wolka'' |''váll'' |''olka'' |''õlg'' |shoulder |} Examples also include 'bit', 'to fear', 'cloud', 'fish', 'winter', 'flat', 'to push', 'bosom' listed above.
* Hungarian nasal consonants {{IPA|/m n ɲ/}} correspond to Finnish and Estonian {{IPA|/m n n/}}: {| class="wikitable" |- !Proto-Uralic !Hungarian !Finnish !Estonian !meaning |- |''*mi'' |''mi'' |''mikä'' : ''mi-'' |''mis'' |what |- |''*mene-'' |''megy'' : ''men-'' |''mennä'' |''minema'' |to go |- |''*mińä'' |''meny'' |''miniä'' |''minia'' |daughter-in-law |- |''*muna'' |''mony'' (dialectal) |''muna'' |''muna'' |egg, testicle |- |''*neljä'' |''négy'' |''neljä'' |''neli'' |four |- |''*nime'' |''név'' |''nimi'' |''nimi'' |name |} Further examples include ({{IPA|/m/}}:) 'honey', 'liver', 'eye', ({{IPA|/n/}}:) 'to plait', 'to see', 'sinew', ({{IPA|/ɲ/}}:) 'tear', 'palate', 'arrow', 'to lick' listed above. Word-internally a correspondence Hungarian {{IPA|/v/}} : Finnic {{IPA|/m/}} is also found, as seen in 'broth', 'name', and 'heart'.
* A correspondence can also be set up between Hungarian {{IPA|/g/}} and Finnish and Estonian long vowels. With the help of the other Uralic languages, this can be reconstructed as *ŋ: {| class="wikitable" |- !Proto-Uralic !Hungarian !Finnish !Estonian !meaning |- |''*jäŋe'' |''jég'' |''jää'' |''jää'' |ice |- |''*piŋe'' |''fog'' |''pii'' |''pii'' |tooth |- |''*püŋe'' |''fogoly'' |''pyy'' |''püü'' |hazelhen |- |''*śäŋe'' |''ég'' |''sää'' | |sky (Hung.), weather (Fi.) |- |''*šiŋere'' |''egér'' |''hiiri'' |''hiir'' |mouse |- |''*wiŋe-'' |''vég'' |''viimeinen'' |''viimane'' |end (Hung.), last (Finnic) |}
