[[File:Saint Petersburg Hermitage Small Throne Room 01.jpg|thumb|right|The Small Throne Room of the Winter Palace (2018)]]

[[File:Small throne.jpg|thumb|right|175px|Location of Small Throne Room, within the Winter Palace]]

The '''Small Throne Room''' of the [[Winter Palace]], [[St Petersburg]], also known as the Peter the Great Memorial Hall, was created for Tsar [[Nicholas I of Russia|Nicholas I]] in 1833, by the architect [[Auguste de Montferrand]].{{r|Museum}} Following a fire in 1837, in which most of the palace was destroyed, the room was recreated exactly as it had been before by the architect [[Vasily Stasov]].

Designed in a loose [[Baroque]] style, the throne is recessed in an [[apse]] before a [[reredos]], supported by two [[Corinthian order|Corinthian]] columns of [[jasper]], which contains a large canvas dedicated to Peter I with [[Minerva]] by [[Jacopo Amigoni]]. In the room proper above [[Dado (architecture)|dado]] height the walls are lined with crimson velvet embellished with double-headed eagles of silver thread, above which is a shallow [[vault (architecture)|vaulted]] ceiling.

Set in the opposing [[lunettes]] beneath the vaulting are paintings depicting the [[Battle of Poltava]] and the [[Battle of Lesnaya]] by Pietro Scotti (1768-1837) and Barnabas Medici. However, the focal point of the room is the [[silver-gilt]] throne of 1731, made in London by the Anglo-French gold-and-silver-smith Nicholas Clausen.{{efn|As to the history of the throne, the State Hermitage Museum [https://web.archive.org/web/20050206022353/http://www.hermitagemuseum.org/html_En/05/hm5_1_17.html here] contradicts itself [https://web.archive.org/web/20080924225456/http://www.hermitagemuseum.org/html_En/08/hm89_0_1_35.html here]}}

Here, during the era of the Tsars, [[diplomat]]s gathered on New Years Day to offer good wishes to the Tsar.{{sfnp|Budberg|1969|p=201|ps=}} Today, as part of the [[State Hermitage Museum]], this room retains its original decoration.

